{"config":{"separator":"[\\s\\-_,:!=\\[\\]()\\\\\"`/]+|\\.(?!\\d)"},"items":[{"location":"","level":1,"title":"The Space Between","text":"<p>Welcome to my personal website for keeping and sharing notes, learnings and tips I've picked up along the way. </p> <p>This is a collection of explainers, tutorials, quick notes (mostly for my brain to understand) and code snippets on concepts I've found useful to formalise. </p>","path":["The Space Between"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/","level":1,"title":"A Crash Course in Git","text":"","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#what-is-git","level":2,"title":"What is Git?","text":"<p>Git is a piece of software on your machine used to track changes in files. Git let's us: </p> <ul> <li>See what's changed, when and by whom</li> <li>Compare different versions of your work</li> <li>Collaborate with other people without overwriting each other's changes</li> <li>Maintain a complete audit trail of a project</li> <li>Revert mistakes</li> </ul>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#key-terms","level":3,"title":"Key Terms","text":"Term Definition Repository (Repo) A project tracked by Git Commit A snapshot of changes at a point in time Branch An isolated line of development Merge Combining changes from different branches Clone Creating a local copy of a repository Push Uploading changes to a remote repository Pull Downloading changes from a remote repository","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#why-should-i-use-git","level":2,"title":"Why Should I Use Git?","text":"<p>Git is good for tracking changes with:</p> <ul> <li>Scripts (Python,R,SQL)</li> <li>Notebooks (Rmd, Jupyter Notebooks)</li> <li>FME workspaces</li> <li>Configuration files</li> <li>Documentation</li> </ul>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#1-change-history","level":3,"title":"1. Change History","text":"<p>Every modification is recorded with:</p> <ul> <li>What changed</li> <li>Who changed it</li> <li>When it changed</li> <li>Why it changed (through commit messages - free text from the author)</li> </ul>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#2-rollbacks","level":3,"title":"2. Rollbacks","text":"<p>Git allows you to quickly return to a previous working version without manually restoring files.</p>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#3-safe-experimentation","level":3,"title":"3. Safe Experimentation","text":"<p>Create a branch and experiment freely without altering the main/production branch. </p>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#4-better-collaboration","level":3,"title":"4. Better Collaboration","text":"<p>Git solves the classic problem of multiple people editing the same files. Git helps coordinate changes.</p>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#git-and-github","level":2,"title":"Git and GitHub","text":"Question <p>\"What's the difference between Git and GitHub?\"</p> <p>Git is the actual version control software installed on your machine.</p> <p>It manages version history, branches, commits and merges. </p> <p>Git works perfectly well without an internet connection.</p> <p>GitHub is a cloud platform built around Git.</p> <p>It is a platform where repositories can be hosted, developers can collaborate, Pull Requests (PRs) and Issues can be rasied and tracked and other Continuous Integration /Continuous Development (CI/CD) apabilities. </p> <p>An analogy:</p> Git GitHub Engine Car Version control technology Collaboration platform Works locally Lives online Tracks changes Helps teams work together <p>Other Git hosting platforms exist too:</p> <ul> <li>GitHub</li> <li>Azure DevOps</li> <li>GitLab</li> <li>Bitbucket</li> </ul>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#standard-workflow","level":3,"title":"Standard Workflow","text":"<pre><code>Clone Repository\n       ↓\nCreate Branch\n       ↓\nMake Changes\n       ↓\nCommit Changes\n       ↓\nPush Branch\n       ↓\nOpen Pull Request\n       ↓\nCode Review\n       ↓\nMerge into Main\n</code></pre>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#git-flow","level":2,"title":"Git Flow","text":"<p>A branching strategy that defines how code moves from development into production.</p>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#core-branches","level":3,"title":"Core Branches","text":"","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#main","level":4,"title":"main","text":"<p>Contains production-ready code.</p> <p>Anything in <code>main</code> should be QA'ed, stable and deployable.</p>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#develop","level":4,"title":"develop","text":"<p>Contains the latest development work.</p> <p>Features are merged here before eventually being released.</p>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#supporting-branches","level":3,"title":"Supporting Branches","text":"","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#feature-branches","level":4,"title":"Feature Branches","text":"<p>Used for developing new functionality.</p> <p>Example:</p> <pre><code>feature/add-tracking-module\nfeature/add-health-classification\n</code></pre>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#release-branches","level":4,"title":"Release Branches","text":"<p>Created when preparing a release.</p> <p>Used for:</p> <ul> <li>Final testing</li> <li>Documentation updates</li> <li>Minor fixes</li> </ul> <p>Example:</p> <pre><code>release/v2.0\n</code></pre>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#hotfix-branches","level":4,"title":"Hotfix Branches","text":"<p>Created from production when urgent issues occur.</p> <p>Example:</p> <pre><code>hotfix/fix-critical-bug\n</code></pre>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Git/#git-flow-diagram","level":3,"title":"Git Flow Diagram","text":"<pre><code>main\n │\n ├───────────────┐\n │               │\n │           hotfix/*\n │               │\n │               ▼\n └───────────────●\n\ndevelop\n │\n ├── feature/*\n ├── feature/*\n └── feature/*\n\n       │\n       ▼\n\n    release/*\n       │\n       ▼\n\n      main\n</code></pre> Question <p>When Should You Use Git Flow?</p> <p>Git Flow works well when:</p> <ul> <li>Multiple developers contribute</li> <li>Formal releases are required</li> <li>Production stability is important</li> </ul> <p>For smaller projects or on projects where you are the sole developer, simpler workflows such as are often faster and easier to manage.</p>","path":["Coding","A Crash Course in Git"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/Useful%20Git%20Commands/","level":1,"title":"Useful Git Commands","text":"","path":["Coding","Useful Git Commands"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/Useful%20Git%20Commands/#useful-git-commands","level":2,"title":"Useful Git Commands","text":"","path":["Coding","Useful Git Commands"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/Useful%20Git%20Commands/#setup","level":3,"title":"Setup","text":"<p>Initialise a new repository:</p> <pre><code>git init\n</code></pre> <p>Clone an existing repository:</p> <pre><code>git clone &lt;repository-url&gt;\n</code></pre> <p>Check your Git version:</p> <pre><code>git --version\n</code></pre>","path":["Coding","Useful Git Commands"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/Useful%20Git%20Commands/#commonly-used","level":3,"title":"Commonly Used","text":"<p>Check repository status:</p> <pre><code>git status\n</code></pre> <p>See recent commits:</p> <pre><code>git log\n</code></pre> <p>Add all changed files:</p> <pre><code>git add .\n</code></pre> <p>Add a specific file:</p> <pre><code>git add myfile.py\n</code></pre> <p>Create a commit:</p> <pre><code>git commit -m \"Add feature X\"\n</code></pre>","path":["Coding","Useful Git Commands"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/Useful%20Git%20Commands/#branching","level":3,"title":"Branching","text":"<p>View branches:</p> <pre><code>git branch\n</code></pre> <p>Create a new branch:</p> <pre><code>git checkout -b feature/new-feature\n</code></pre> <p>Switch branches:</p> <pre><code>git checkout develop\n</code></pre> <p>Merge a branch:</p> <pre><code>git merge feature/new-feature\n</code></pre> <p>Delete a branch:</p> <pre><code>git branch -d feature/new-feature\n</code></pre>","path":["Coding","Useful Git Commands"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/Useful%20Git%20Commands/#pushing-and-pulling","level":3,"title":"Pushing and Pulling","text":"<p>Download latest changes:</p> <pre><code>git pull\n</code></pre> <p>Upload commits:</p> <pre><code>git push\n</code></pre> <p>Push a new branch:</p> <pre><code>git push -u origin feature/new-feature\n</code></pre>","path":["Coding","Useful Git Commands"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/Useful%20Git%20Commands/#comparing-changes","level":3,"title":"Comparing Changes","text":"<p>Compare branches:</p> <pre><code>git diff main develop\n</code></pre>","path":["Coding","Useful Git Commands"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/Useful%20Git%20Commands/#undoing-mistakes","level":3,"title":"Undoing Mistakes","text":"<p>Undo changes to a file:</p> <pre><code>git checkout -- myfile.py\n</code></pre> <p>Unstage a file:</p> <pre><code>git reset myfile.py\n</code></pre> <p>Revert a commit safely:</p> <pre><code>git revert &lt;commit-id&gt;\n</code></pre>","path":["Coding","Useful Git Commands"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/Useful%20Git%20Commands/#the-save-my-work-quickly-commands","level":3,"title":"The \"Save My Work Quickly\" Commands","text":"<p>Temporarily save changes:</p> <pre><code>git stash\n</code></pre> <p>Restore stashed changes:</p> <pre><code>git stash pop\n</code></pre>","path":["Coding","Useful Git Commands"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Coding/Useful%20Git%20Commands/#do-the-dance","level":2,"title":"\"Do the dance\"","text":"<p>This is my favourite. Used when I need to update branch without losing local changes: </p> <pre><code>git stash #this stashes the changes in my current branch\ngit checkout main #checks out the main branch\ngit pull \ngit checkout myoriginalbranch\ngit stash pop \ngit merge main #brings in all the changes from main into current branch\n</code></pre>","path":["Coding","Useful Git Commands"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Geospatial/Habitat%20suitability%20and%20connectivity%20modelling/","level":1,"title":"Content coming soon!","text":"<p>New content coming very soon...</p>","path":["Geospatial","Content coming soon!"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Machine%20learning/A%20crash%20course%20in%20neural%20networks/","level":1,"title":"Content coming soon!","text":"<p>New content coming very soon...</p>","path":["Machine learning","Content coming soon!"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Machine%20learning/Computer%20vision/Unwarping%20360%20images/","level":1,"title":"Content coming soon!","text":"<p>New content coming very soon...</p>","path":["Machine learning","Computer vision","Content coming soon!"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/","level":1,"title":"Stats shouldn't be scary!","text":"<p>Some text here </p>","path":["Statistics","Stats shouldn't be scary!"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/","level":1,"title":"A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics","text":"<p>Recently, I worked on several projects where we used bayesian models for prediction. I've had to explain bayesian statistics to many stakeholders (with varying degrees of compleixty) so I thought it would be helpful to formalise this into a little crash course. </p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#introduction","level":2,"title":"Introduction","text":"<p>Bayesian statistics provides a framework for updating our beliefs as new evidence becomes available. </p> <p>Rather than treating parameters as fixed but unknown values, Bayesian methods treat them as probabilities that can change as new information is observed.</p> <p>The key question for Bayesian stats is: </p> Question <p>\"Given what I already know, and given the new evidence I have collected, what should I believe now?\"</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#how-is-bayesian-different-to-frequentist-statistics","level":2,"title":"How is Bayesian Different to Frequentist Statistics?","text":"<p>The main difference is how probability is interpreted.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#frequentist-statistics","level":3,"title":"Frequentist Statistics","text":"<p>Frequentist statistics views probability as the long-run frequency of events.</p> <p>For example:</p> Question <p>\"If we repeated an experiment thousands of times, how often would a particular outcome occur?\"</p> <p>Unknown quantities (such as a regression coefficient or population mean) are considered fixed values. We estimate them using data and quantify uncertainty through confidence intervals and p-values.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#bayesian-statistics","level":3,"title":"Bayesian Statistics","text":"<p>Bayesian statistics views probability as a degree of belief.</p> <p>For example:</p> Question <p>\"Given what I know right now, how likely is it that this statement is true?\"</p> <p>Unknown quantities are represented as probability distributions rather than fixed values.</p> <p>As new data becomes available, our beliefs are updated.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#example-smoking-and-lung-cancer","level":3,"title":"Example: Smoking and Lung Cancer","text":"<p>Imagine you have two patients:  - Patient A: Never smoked - Patient B: Chian smoked for 40 years. </p> <p>Before we conduct any medical tests, which patient do you think you'd be more concerned about just based on those two pieces of information? Intuitively, you would say Patient B immediately. This is because we already know that smoking is a major risk factor for lung cancer, so this existing knowledge forms our prior belief. </p> <p>Suppose both patients go for scan which scans for lung cancer. The scan provides us with new evidence. </p> <p>So, bayesian statistics combines what we already know (patiet's smoking history) and new evidence we have just observed (scan results) to calculate an updated probability for lung cancer. </p> <ul> <li>A Frequentist asks: \"If someone has lung cancer, how often would this scan produce a positive result\"</li> <li>A Bayesian asks: \"Given that this patient is a long-term smoker and has a positive scan, what is the probability they have lung cancer?\"</li> </ul>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#comparing-the-two-approaches","level":3,"title":"Comparing the Two Approaches","text":"Question Frequentist Bayesian What is probability? Long-run frequency Degree of belief Parameters Fixed but unknown Probability distributions Prior knowledge Not formally included Explicitly incorporated Typical outputs p-values, confidence intervals Posterior distributions, credible intervals Interpretation Probability of the data Probability of the hypothesis","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#bayes-theorem","level":2,"title":"Bayes' Theorem","text":"<p>Bayesian inference is built upon Bayes' Theorem:</p> \\[ P(A \\mid B)=\\frac{P(B \\mid A)P(A)}{P(B)} \\] <p>Where:</p> Term Meaning \\(P(A)\\) Prior belief \\(P(B \\mid A)\\) Likelihood of observing the evidence \\(P(B)\\) Probability of observing the evidence \\(P(A \\mid B)\\) Updated belief (Posterior) <p>Often summarised as:</p> \\[ \\text{Posterior} \\propto \\text{Likelihood} \\times \\text{Prior} \\]","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#bayesian-updating","level":3,"title":"Bayesian Updating","text":"<pre><code>flowchart LR\n    A[Prior Belief]\n    B[New Evidence]\n    C[Bayes' Theorem]\n    D[Posterior Belief]\n\n    A --&gt; C\n    B --&gt; C\n    C --&gt; D\n</code></pre> <p>The posterior from one analysis can become the prior for the next, allowing knowledge to accumulate over time.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#example-1-predicting-the-presence-of-a-species-in-an-area","level":2,"title":"Example 1: Predicting the Presence of a Species in an Area","text":"<p>Suppose an we are assessing whether a rare bat species is present within a woodland.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#prior-knowledge","level":3,"title":"Prior Knowledge","text":"<p>Based on historical surveys in similar habitats, we know that:</p> <p>Probability the species is present = 70%</p> <pre><code>Prior = 0.70\n</code></pre>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#new-evidence","level":3,"title":"New Evidence","text":"<p>An acoustic detector records several calls matching the target species.</p> <p>Previous validation studies show:</p> <p>If the species is present, the detector identifies it correctly 90% of the time.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#bayesian-update","level":3,"title":"Bayesian Update","text":"<p>The new evidence increases our confidence that the species is present.</p> <pre><code>flowchart TD\n    A[Habitat Information]\n    B[Prior Probability: 70%]\n    C[Acoustic Survey Results]\n    D[Updated Probability of Presence]\n\n    A --&gt; B\n    B --&gt; D\n    C --&gt; D\n</code></pre> <p>Unlike a simple \"present\" or \"absent\" classification, Bayesian analysis provides a probability that reflects both historical knowledge and newly collected evidence.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#example-2-predicting-voter-choice","level":2,"title":"Example 2: Predicting Voter Choice","text":"<p>Imagine we want to predict which UK political party a voter is most likely to support.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#prior-beliefs","level":3,"title":"Prior Beliefs","text":"<p>Before speaking to the voter, we might use national polling data:</p> Party Prior Probability Labour 40% Conservative 25% Liberal Democrat 15% Green 10% Other 10%","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#new-evidence_1","level":3,"title":"New Evidence","text":"<p>The voter tells us:</p> <p>\"Climate change is my most important issue.\"</p> <p>Historically, voters who prioritise climate issues are more likely to support the Green Party or Labour than the Conservatives.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#posterior-beliefs","level":3,"title":"Posterior Beliefs","text":"<p>After updating our beliefs:</p> Party Updated Probability Labour 45% Conservative 10% Liberal Democrat 15% Green 25% Other 5%","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#bayesian-voting-example","level":3,"title":"Bayesian Voting Example","text":"<pre><code>flowchart LR\n    A[Polling Data]\n    B[Prior Party Probabilities]\n\n    C[Voter Prioritises Climate Change]\n\n    D[Updated Party Probabilities]\n\n    A --&gt; B\n    B --&gt; D\n    C --&gt; D\n</code></pre> <p>Bayesian inference combines existing knowledge with new evidence to produce a revised estimate of what is most likely.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#limitations-of-bayesian-statistics","level":2,"title":"Limitations of Bayesian Statistics","text":"<p>Bayesian methods are powerful, but they are not always the best choice.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#1-priors-can-be-subjective","level":3,"title":"1. Priors Can Be Subjective","text":"<p>Bayesian models require prior assumptions.</p> <p>Different analysts may choose different priors, which can lead to different conclusions, particularly when little data is available.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    A[Analyst 1 Prior]\n    B[Same Data]\n    C[Posterior A]\n\n    D[Analyst 2 Prior]\n    E[Posterior B]\n\n    A --&gt; B\n    B --&gt; C\n\n    D --&gt; B\n    B --&gt; E\n</code></pre> <p>When datasets are small, results may be strongly influenced by these prior assumptions.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#2-computationally-intensive","level":3,"title":"2. Computationally Intensive","text":"<p>Many Bayesian models require simulation methods such as:</p> <ul> <li>Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC)</li> <li>Hamiltonian Monte Carlo (HMC)</li> <li>Variational Inference</li> </ul> <p>These can be significantly more computationally expensive than equivalent frequentist methods.</p> <p>For large datasets or highly complex models, run times can become substantial.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#3-results-can-be-sensitive-to-model-specification","level":3,"title":"3. Results Can Be Sensitive to Model Specification","text":"<p>Bayesian models require decisions about:</p> <ul> <li>Priors</li> <li>Likelihood functions</li> <li>Hierarchical structures</li> </ul> <p>Poorly chosen assumptions can bias results, particularly when data is limited.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#4-frequentist-methods-are-often-simpler","level":3,"title":"4. Frequentist Methods Are Often Simpler","text":"<p>For many routine analyses:</p> <ul> <li>Two-sample t-tests</li> <li>Linear regression</li> <li>ANOVA</li> <li>Chi-squared tests</li> </ul> <p>Frequentist approaches are often easier to implement, explain and reproduce.</p> <p>If the objective is simply to estimate a parameter using a large dataset, a frequentist solution may be perfectly adequate.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#why-bayesian-statistics-is-useful","level":2,"title":"Why Bayesian Statistics is Useful","text":"<p>Despite its limitations, Bayesian statistics offers several compelling advantages:</p> <ul> <li>Prior knowledge can be formally incorporated into analysis.</li> <li>Probabilities are intuitive and easy to interpret.</li> <li>Uncertainty is represented naturally through probability distributions.</li> <li>Predictions can be continuously updated as new information becomes available.</li> <li>Complex hierarchical and multi-level systems can be modelled effectively.</li> </ul>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#bayesian-learning-cycle","level":3,"title":"Bayesian Learning Cycle","text":"<pre><code>flowchart LR\n    A[Prior Knowledge]\n    B[Collect Data]\n    C[Calculate Posterior]\n    D[Updated Understanding]\n\n    A --&gt; B\n    B --&gt; C\n    C --&gt; D\n    D --&gt; A\n</code></pre>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/A%20crash%20course%20in%20Bayesian%20statistics/#key-takeaway","level":2,"title":"Key Takeaway","text":"<p>Bayesian statistics is fundamentally a framework for learning.</p> <p>Rather than asking:</p> <p>\"Would this result be unusual if my hypothesis were true?\"</p> <p>Bayesian statistics asks:</p> <p>\"Given my existing knowledge and the evidence I've observed, what should I believe now?\"</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","A Crash Course in Bayesian Statistics"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/Bayesian%20sequential%20updating/","level":1,"title":"Bayesian Sequential Updating","text":"<p>One of the most powerful features of Bayesian statistics is that it allows us to continuously update our beliefs as new evidence becomes available.</p> <p>In Bayesian Sequential Updating, the posterior distribution from today becomes the prior distribution for tomorrow.</p> <p>Rather than analysing all available data from scratch every time new information arrives, we  update our existing beliefs with the latest evidence.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","Bayesian Sequential Updating"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/Bayesian%20sequential%20updating/#key-intuition","level":2,"title":"Key Intuition","text":"<p>Bayesian inference follows a simple principle:</p> \\[ \\text{Posterior} \\propto \\text{Likelihood} \\times \\text{Prior} \\] <p>When a new observation becomes available:</p> <ol> <li>Start with a prior belief.</li> <li>Collect new evidence.</li> <li>Calculate a posterior belief.</li> <li>Treat the posterior as the new prior.</li> <li>Repeat.</li> </ol>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","Bayesian Sequential Updating"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/Bayesian%20sequential%20updating/#sequential-updating-process","level":3,"title":"Sequential Updating Process","text":"<pre><code>flowchart LR\n\n    A[Prior]\n    B[New Data]\n    C[Posterior]\n\n    C --&gt; D[New Prior]\n    E[More Data]\n    F[Updated Posterior]\n\n    A --&gt; C\n    B --&gt; C\n\n    D --&gt; F\n    E --&gt; F\n</code></pre>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","Bayesian Sequential Updating"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/Bayesian%20sequential%20updating/#example-smoking-and-lung-cancer","level":2,"title":"Example: Smoking and Lung Cancer","text":"<p>I am diagnosing an individual for lung cancer. </p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","Bayesian Sequential Updating"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/Bayesian%20sequential%20updating/#step-1-prior-belief","level":3,"title":"Step 1: Prior Belief","text":"<p>The individual is a chain smoker who has smoked for 40 years.</p> <p>Based on historical evidence, we already believe:</p> <p>This patient has a higher risk of lung cancer than the average person.</p> <p>This forms the prior probability.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    A[Smoking History]\n    B[Prior Probability of Lung Cancer]\n\n    A --&gt; B\n</code></pre>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","Bayesian Sequential Updating"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/Bayesian%20sequential%20updating/#step-2-new-evidence-arrives","level":3,"title":"Step 2: New Evidence Arrives","text":"<p>A chest X-ray reveals a suspicious shadow.</p> <p>We can update our belief. </p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    A[Prior Risk]\n    B[Chest X-ray Result]\n    C[Updated Probability]\n\n    A --&gt; C\n    B --&gt; C\n</code></pre> <p>The resulting probability is called the posterior probability.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","Bayesian Sequential Updating"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/Bayesian%20sequential%20updating/#step-3-more-evidence-arrives","level":3,"title":"Step 3: More Evidence Arrives","text":"<p>A CT scan is performed.</p> <p>Instead of returning to the beginning and ignoring what has already been learned, we can use the previous posterior as the new prior.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    A[Posterior After X-ray]\n    B[CT Scan]\n    C[New Posterior]\n\n    A --&gt; C\n    B --&gt; C\n</code></pre> <p>Risk estimates are refined further.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","Bayesian Sequential Updating"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/Bayesian%20sequential%20updating/#step-4-a-biopsy-result-arrives","level":3,"title":"Step 4: A Biopsy Result Arrives","text":"<p>Finally, a biopsy is performed.</p> <p>Again, the previous posterior becomes the new prior.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    A[Posterior After CT]\n    B[Biopsy Results]\n    C[Final Posterior Probability]\n\n    A --&gt; C\n    B --&gt; C\n</code></pre> <p>At each stage, the estimate becomes more informed because it incorporates all previous evidence.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","Bayesian Sequential Updating"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/Bayesian%20sequential%20updating/#why-sequential-updating-is-useful","level":2,"title":"Why Sequential Updating Is Useful","text":"<p>Traditional statistical analysis often works like this:</p> <pre><code>Collect all data\n↓\nRun analysis\n↓\nGenerate result\n</code></pre> <p>Bayesian Sequential Updating works differently:</p> <pre><code>Observation 1 → Update\nObservation 2 → Update\nObservation 3 → Update\nObservation 4 → Update\n...\n</code></pre> <p>This is good for when information arrives gradually over time, or we have varying degrees of confidence on our observations.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","Bayesian Sequential Updating"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/Bayesian%20sequential%20updating/#real-world-applications","level":2,"title":"Real-World Applications","text":"","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","Bayesian Sequential Updating"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/Bayesian%20sequential%20updating/#ecology","level":3,"title":"Ecology","text":"<p>Suppose we want to determine whether a rare bat species is present.</p> <p>Evidence may arrive in stages:</p> <ol> <li>Habitat assessment</li> <li>Acoustic recordings</li> <li>Emergence surveys</li> <li>eDNA sampling</li> </ol> <p>Each survey incrementally updates our confidence in species presence.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","Bayesian Sequential Updating"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/Bayesian%20sequential%20updating/#asset-management","level":3,"title":"Asset Management","text":"<p>Sequential updating is particularly useful for infrastructure assets.</p> <p>An asset may initially have a baseline health assessment.</p> <p>Over time, new information arrives from:</p> <ul> <li>Visual examinations</li> <li>Train bourne monitoring systems</li> <li>LiDAR surveys</li> <li>Sensors</li> <li>Failure records</li> </ul> <p>Each observation can update the estimated asset condition rather than requiring a complete rebuild of the model.</p>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","Bayesian Sequential Updating"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Bayesian/Bayesian%20sequential%20updating/#visualising-belief-updating","level":2,"title":"Visualising Belief Updating","text":"<p>A useful way to think about Bayesian updating is as a process of reducing uncertainty.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n\n    A[Very Uncertain Prior]\n    B[Observation 1]\n    C[Observation 2]\n    D[Observation 3]\n    E[High Confidence Posterior]\n\n    A --&gt; B\n    B --&gt; C\n    C --&gt; D\n    D --&gt; E\n</code></pre> <p>As more evidence accumulates:</p> <ul> <li>Uncertainty decreases.</li> <li>The posterior distribution becomes more concentrated (i.e., the distribution is less wide as we are more confident about where we'll end up).</li> <li>Our estimates become more precise.</li> </ul>","path":["Statistics","Bayesian","Bayesian Sequential Updating"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Causal/Difference%20in%20differences/","level":1,"title":"Content coming soon!","text":"<p>New content coming very soon...</p>","path":["Statistics","Causal","Content coming soon!"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Causal/Synthetic%20control%20analysis/","level":1,"title":"Content coming soon!","text":"<p>New content coming very soon...</p>","path":["Statistics","Causal","Content coming soon!"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Fundamentals/Hypothesis%20testing/","level":1,"title":"Content coming soon!","text":"<p>New content coming very soon...</p>","path":["Statistics","Fundamentals","Content coming soon!"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Fundamentals/Regression/","level":1,"title":"Content coming soon!","text":"<p>New content coming very soon...</p>","path":["Statistics","Fundamentals","Content coming soon!"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Statistics/Fundamentals/Significance/","level":1,"title":"Content coming soon!","text":"<p>New content coming very soon...</p>","path":["Statistics","Fundamentals","Content coming soon!"],"tags":[]},{"location":"Talks/A%20flapping%20good%20model/","level":1,"title":"\"A Flapping Good Model: Collaborative approaches to machine learning for biodiversity\"","text":"<p>A talk given jointly with my colleague Sam Smith at GeoBusiness 2026 in London, UK. </p>","path":["Talks","\"A Flapping Good Model: Collaborative approaches to machine learning for biodiversity\""],"tags":[]},{"location":"Talks/A%20flapping%20good%20model/#abstract","level":2,"title":"Abstract","text":"<p>Mott MacDonald showcase an innovative cross-disciplinary framework revolutionising habitat suitability modelling. Using advanced machine learning combined with ecological expertise, they’ve delivered a more robust, cost-effective survey and mitigation strategy for a major UK railway project.</p> <p>With 1 million species threatened globally and 69% of UK species in decline, traditional approaches aren’t enough. Learn how their integrated INLA and CircuitScape methodology identifies critical habitat corridors, reduces project risks and costs, and delivers measurable benefits for both the client and nature.</p>","path":["Talks","\"A Flapping Good Model: Collaborative approaches to machine learning for biodiversity\""],"tags":[]},{"location":"Talks/A%20flapping%20good%20model/#details","level":2,"title":"Details","text":"<p>Mott MacDonald have developed an innovative cross-disciplinary approach to habitat suitability modelling (HSM) that brings together expertise and innovation across the fields of geospatial, data science and ecology. By combining advanced machine learning with ecological expertise, we delivered a robust and actionable survey and mitigation strategy for a nationally significant linear infrastructure project in the UK. This presentation aims to showcase how we married advanced spatial data science and ecology to deliver a data-led, focussed and risk-based survey effort to inform design considerations of a major project from the outset – allowing us to design in permeability and connectivity, and design out impacts. </p> <p>The climate crisis and biodiversity loss through development projects is at the forefront of project design, not least through the introduction of the Environment Act 2021 but also more recently through the Planning and Infrastructure Act 2025 . According to the IPBES Global Assessment, approximately 1 million species are threatened with extinction, with habitat fragmentation a primary driver. In the UK, 69% of species have declined since 1970 with transport infrastructure contributing significantly to habitat loss and fragmentation across landscapes. Today, drivers for development outpace any previously encountered. It is imperative that we develop innovative approaches that allow us to adopt systematic, transparent, robust and repeatable baseline assessment methods to identify areas for survey based on risk, challenge and define mitigation and provide data driven approaches to inform early discussions with stakeholders and design of major projects. </p> <p>Ecological assessments attempt to understand how a development may impact the natural environment and inform necessary mitigations. Traditionally, these assessments have often operated in isolation from empirical and advanced modelling capabilities. Although there are a variety of statistical methods which can be used for modelling habitat suitability, striking the balance between ecological nuance needed for actionable outcomes and statistical robustness is difficult. This disconnects results in suboptimal decision-making, increased project risks and missed opportunities for a positive environmental impact. </p> <p>We developed an unique framework and way of working, combining Integrated Nested Laplace Approximation (INLA), CircuitScape and ecological knowledge to predict bat species distributions across our project and the adjacent landscapes. Our approach allows us to quantitatively identify critical habitat corridors and potential fragmentation hotspots to ensure appropriate and justified mitigation is designed for the scheme.</p> <p>In the presentation, we hope to show how a cross-disciplinary way of working delivers measurable benefits. First, we show how we built models that are both statistically robust and ecologically meaningful. We will also outline how our automated pipeline scales across large geographic areas and ingest a variety of datasets. Lastly, we’ll showcase how we use this data to drive ecological insights that help us answer some of engineering’s biggest questions. </p>","path":["Talks","\"A Flapping Good Model: Collaborative approaches to machine learning for biodiversity\""],"tags":[]},{"location":"Talks/A%20flapping%20good%20model/#slides","level":2,"title":"Slides","text":"","path":["Talks","\"A Flapping Good Model: Collaborative approaches to machine learning for biodiversity\""],"tags":[]}]}
